  "prompt": "How does a hydraulic brake work? Describe in brief",
  "response": "A hydraulic brake system works by using fluid to transfer force from the brake pedal to the brake mechanism. Here is a brief description of the process:\n\n1. **Brake Pedal:** When the driver presses the brake pedal, it pushes a piston in the master cylinder.\n2. **Master Cylinder:** This piston compresses the brake fluid (usually a special hydraulic fluid) inside the master cylinder.\n3. **Brake Lines:** The compressed fluid travels through brake lines and hoses to the brake calipers or wheel cylinders at each wheel.\n4. **Brake Calipers/Wheel Cylinders:** The hydraulic pressure forces pistons in the brake calipers or wheel cylinders to push the brake pads or shoes against the rotating discs or drums.\n5. **Friction:** The contact between the brake pads and discs (or shoes and drums) creates friction, which slows down the rotation of the wheels and ultimately stops the vehicle.\n\nThe hydraulic brake system is effective because liquids are incompressible, meaning the force applied to the brake pedal is efficiently transmitted to the brakes themselves, ensuring consistent and reliable braking performance.",
